ome characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sandford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in England with names derived from Old English <i>sand</i> ‘sand’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford, river crossing’, such as Sandford in Warcop (Westmorland), Sandford in Sonning and Dry Sandford in Abingdon (both Berkshire), Sandford on Thames and Sandford Saint Martin (both Oxfordshire), Great and Little Sampford (Essex), Sandford Orcas (Dorset), Sandford, Sampford Courtney, Sampford Peverell, and Sampford Spiney (all Devon), Sampford Arundel and Sampford Brett (both Somerset), and Sandford (Shropshire). See also   Sandiford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Samford","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sanderford","meanings":["English: variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sanford","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sandiford","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Sandifer  ."]}]},{"name":"Christian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Christianus</i> ‘follower of Christ’, in use as a given name from the Middle Ages onwards, especially as a girl's name. The name of <i>Christ</i> (Greek <i>Khristos</i>) is a translation of the Hebrew term <i>Messiah</i> ‘anointed’."],"variants":